\begin_layout Abstract
Quality measurement is necessary but insufficient for creating markets
 for quality in agricultural value chains.
 We conduct two experiments in Ugandan dairy supply chains.
 First, a cluster-randomized trial deploying milk analyzers at 120 collection
 centers improves milk quality by 0.21 SD but generates no price premiums---gains
 arise entirely through enforcement, not pricing.
 Second, a trader-level experiment exogenously providing quality-based premiums
 increases quality when thresholds bind, yet premiums do not pass through
 to farmers.
 We develop a model nesting enforcement and pricing channels to rationalize
 both findings.
 Quality upgrading and price transmission require fundamentally separate
 policy interventions.
\end_layout

