\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:introduction"

\end_inset

Quality is central to value chain development.
 Higher-quality inputs improve processing efficiency, reduce waste, and support
 compliance with domestic and export standards; maintaining quality during
 aggregation, storage, and transport is critical for food safety
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{REARDON2000195,MINTEN20091728}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Yet in many agricultural supply chains in developing countries, quality
 remains difficult to observe at the point of first sale, and early aggregation
 of output from multiple suppliers makes it nearly impossible to trace quality
 back to individual producers.
 These features give rise to a classic lemons problem
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{2b080e07-2197-39e6-8e29-cfa83db9de24}
\end_layout

\end_inset

: upstream actors cannot be rewarded for supplying higher-quality output,
 so they underinvest in quality-enhancing practices.
 A natural hypothesis, prominent in both the industrial-organization literature
 and in policy discussions around value chain upgrading, is that making quality
 measurable and traceable should trigger the endogenous emergence of quality-differentiated
 pricing---in short, a
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

market for quality
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{bold2022market,10.1093/qje/qjaa048,macchiavello2015value}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 If buyers can verify what they are purchasing, price premiums for quality
 should follow, realigning incentives throughout the chain
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1574-0862.2007.00237.x}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Yet the conditions under which quality observability actually translates
 into quality-based pricing remain poorly understood, particularly in the
 smallholder-dominated supply chains where the information frictions are
 most severe.
 This paper provides the first experimental test of this measurement-to-pricing
 hypothesis---and finds that the hypothesis fails.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We study this question using two sequential field experiments in Ugandan
 dairy supply chains.
 Experiment 1 is a cluster-randomized controlled trial in which we deploy
 digital milk analyzers and a quality monitoring system at approximately
 120 randomly selected Milk Collection Centers (MCCs)---the nodes where
 smallholder milk from roughly 800 farmers is first aggregated---cross-randomized
 with a farmer-level information treatment designed to align producers'
 understanding of quality with processor priorities.
 Experiment 2 is a trader-level RCT conducted at 19 MCCs that already have
 the measurement infrastructure in place, in which we randomly assign explicit
 quality-based bonus payments to 99 milk traders---the intermediaries linking
 farmers to MCCs---and track daily delivery records and endline surveys
 over approximately 30 days.
 Together, the two experiments allow us to separate the effects of quality
 observability from the effects of quality-based pricing, and to trace
 how price signals do or do not transmit upstream through the chain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The setting is Uganda's southwestern milk shed, an area that has undergone
 rapid value chain transformation over the past decade as foreign direct
 investment has spurred the development of modern dairy processing
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12638}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 A dense network of MCCs now connects smallholder dairy farmers to a growing
 cluster of processors.
 In dairy, quality is economically important: compositional attributes---butterfat,
 protein, solids-not-fat---determine processing yields for products such
 as cheese, casein, and infant formula.
 Yet unlike more developed dairy markets, there is generally no functioning
 market for quality in Uganda.
 Prices are fixed per liter, irrespective of composition.
 Part of the problem lies in divergent quality perceptions: farmers associate
 quality with hygiene---clean containers, washed udders---while processors
 prioritize compositional parameters driven largely by feeding practices
 and breed.
 Another part lies in the lack of technological capacity to measure and
 communicate compositional quality at the point of aggregation: most MCCs
 limit testing to freshness and basic adulteration checks, and farmers rarely
 receive test results.
 When producers and processors are linked only indirectly through layers
 of traders, the likelihood of traceability breaking down increases, and
 traders may not transmit---or may distort---processors' quality signals
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{KEMBRO201777,https://doi.org/10.1111/agec.12731}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiment 1 deploys milk analyzers, digital record-keeping, and farmer-facing
 information campaigns at treatment MCCs.
 The MCC-level intervention is cluster-randomized at the catchment-area
 level; the farmer-level information treatment is cross-randomized within
 MCCs in a 2
\begin_inset Formula $\times$
\end_inset

2 factorial design.
 We collect endline survey data from MCCs and farmers, and we draw independent
 milk samples for laboratory analysis to obtain objective quality measures
 uncontaminated by reporting bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experiment 1 produces three sets of results.
 First, the intervention massively increases quality testing: the probability
 that an MCC tests incoming milk rises by 53.3 percentage points (randomization
 inference
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.001$
\end_inset

) and testing of outgoing milk rises by 28.5 percentage points (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.001$
\end_inset

); an omnibus test across six uptake outcomes rejects the null at
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.039$
\end_inset

 with two of six individually significant.
 Second, milk quality improves substantially: butterfat increases by 0.114
 percentage points (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.002$
\end_inset

), added water falls by 0.488 percentage points (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.011$
\end_inset

), and an Anderson summary index of quality improves by 0.209 standard
 deviations (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.001$
\end_inset

); the omnibus test across five quality outcomes rejects at
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.022$
\end_inset

 with three of five individually significant.
 The pattern of effects---water down, fat up, but solids-not-fat and protein
 unchanged---is consistent with reduced adulteration (less water added to
 milk) rather than deeper shifts in production practices such as improved
 feeding.
 Third, and crucially, prices are completely unresponsive.
 Average farmer sales price (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.215$
\end_inset

), whether the farmer receives a quality bonus (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.439$
\end_inset

), and all four outcomes in the farmer pricing family are individually
 null; the omnibus test yields
\begin_inset Formula $p=1.0$
\end_inset

.
 MCC-level pricing outcomes are similarly null.
 No quality premiums emerge at any stage of the chain.
 The market for quality does not materialize.
 The cross-randomized farmer-level information treatment has no significant
 independent effects on primary outcomes; full factorial results are reported
 in the Online Appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To rationalize these findings, we develop a simple model of MCC behavior
 in which a parameter
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

 governs whether quality measurement is translated into quality-differentiated
 pricing (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha>0$
\end_inset

) or used solely for enforcement through acceptance thresholds (
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

).
 The model nests two channels through which quality measurement can improve
 outcomes: a price channel, in which MCCs pass quality information into
 price schedules that reward higher-quality milk, and an enforcement channel,
 in which MCCs use measurement to credibly threaten rejection of adulterated
 deliveries.
 The Experiment 1 results are consistent with
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

: quality improves because the measurement technology raises the credibility
 of rejection threats, but the downstream price schedule remains flat.
 The model generates a clear testable prediction: if quality-based pricing
 were activated exogenously---that is, if
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 were switched on from outside---we should observe additional quality gains
 and behavioral responses among upstream actors.
 Experiment 2 tests exactly this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Experiment 2, we work with 19 MCCs where the measurement system is already
 operational and randomly assign quality premiums to traders who deliver
 milk to these MCCs.
 Treated traders receive UGX 100 per liter for each 0.1 percentage point
 of butterfat and solids-not-fat above East African standards (3.3 percent
 fat, 8.5 percent SNF), paid daily via mobile money.
 The experiment proceeds in two stages: in Stage 1, thresholds are set at
 the East African standards, coinciding with the rainy season when high-quality
 milk is naturally abundant; in Stage 2, the fat threshold is raised from
 3.3 to 3.9 percent, simulating dry-season scarcity conditions under which
 sourcing high-quality milk requires active effort.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results reveal strikingly different trader responses across the two
 stages.
 In Stage 1, when quality is abundant, treated traders respond primarily
 on the volume margin: daily quantity delivered increases by 126 liters
 (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.005$
\end_inset

), but fat content does not significantly improve (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.263$
\end_inset

).
 With high-quality milk already plentiful, the most profitable response
 is simply to collect more of it.
 In Stage 2, once the higher threshold makes quality scarce, the pattern
 shifts: treated traders deliver milk with significantly higher fat content,
 up 0.169 percentage points (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p<0.001$
\end_inset

), and SNF also improves significantly; all four primary outcomes are individually
 significant and the omnibus test rejects at
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.001$
\end_inset

.
 Traders shift from volume expansion to quality-based sourcing when the
 margin of adjustment that matters changes.
 Yet the most striking finding concerns price transmission.
 Treated traders do not pass the quality premium upstream to farmers.
 If anything, the estimated effect on farm-gate prices is negative: -17
 UGX per liter (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.017$
\end_inset

).
 Even when explicit, exogenous quality premiums are injected into the chain,
 the value chain fails to transmit price signals to the producers who ultimately
 determine raw milk quality.
 Farmer feeding practices show marginally significant improvements (RI
\begin_inset Formula $p=0.076$
\end_inset

 with fixed-effect demeaning), but trader endline outcomes are null across
 all five measures---effects visible in the daily digital data do not survive
 into the endline survey, likely reflecting timing and power limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These results contribute to several literatures.
 First, we provide the first mechanism decomposition for the effects of
 quality measurement technology in agricultural value chains.
 A growing body of work studies quality problems in developing-country markets
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{bold2022market,saenger2013contract,RAO2023708}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and recent contributions examine how measurement and monitoring technologies
 can improve market outcomes
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{jensen2007digital,rustagi2022measuring,duflo2013truth}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Our contribution is to show that quality measurement operates through enforcement---the
 credible threat of rejection---rather than through pricing, a distinction
 that existing work has not drawn.
 This matters for policy: a system that improves quality by excluding low-quality
 output has very different welfare and distributional implications than one
 that rewards quality through higher prices.
 The enforcement channel may harm the most resource-constrained farmers
 who lack the means to improve quality and face exclusion rather than incentives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, we provide the first direct experimental evidence on the price channel.
 By exogenously activating quality-based pricing in Experiment 2, we complement
 the observational evidence in
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citet{saenger2013contract}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 on quality grading in Vietnamese dairy,
 the structural analysis of relational contracting in Kenyan roses by
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citet{macchiavello2015value}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citet{10.1093/qje/qjaa048}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and the evidence on group-level incentives in Indian dairy cooperatives
 from
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citet{RAO2023708}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Unlike these studies, which examine settings where quality pricing emerged
 endogenously or was imposed by processors, we experimentally switch on
 a price channel that the market itself did not generate.
 This allows us to identify the causal effect of quality-based pricing in
 isolation from the institutional conditions that normally accompany it.
 The finding that traders respond to quality premiums---adjusting along
 the volume margin when quality is abundant and along the quality margin
 when it is scarce---confirms that intermediaries are sensitive to price
 incentives, and that the absence of quality-based sourcing in Experiment
 1 reflects the absence of incentives rather than an inability to respond.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, we document a striking failure of price transmission along the value
 chain.
 Quality premiums paid to traders do not reach the farmers who ultimately
 determine raw milk quality; if anything, treated traders pay farmers less.
 This finding highlights that the institutional conditions for transmitting
 price signals upstream constitute a separate and binding constraint, distinct
 from the information frictions that quality measurement addresses
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{swinnen2007globalization,casaburi2019infrequent}
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The result resonates with work on intermediary behavior and information
 distortion in value chains
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

~
\backslash
citep{KEMBRO201777,Ponte01022005,Gereffi01022005}
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and with the broader literature on how the organization of global value
 chains shapes the scope for upstream actors to capture rents from quality
 upgrading.
 Together, our findings imply that quality measurement technology is necessary
 but not sufficient for creating markets for quality.
 Measurement moves the system from a pooling equilibrium toward enforcement-based
 screening, but the further step---from enforcement to quality-differentiated
 pricing that reaches producers---requires separate policy attention to
 the institutional and organizational conditions that govern how price signals
 are formed and transmitted through intermediated chains.
\end_layout

